Title: Creed - Official Trailer [HD]
Comment: This is an awesome movie. The Rocky legacy continues, but so does the Apollo Creed legacy when Apollo's son Adonis played by Michael B. Jordan seeks out Rocky to train him to fight, at first Rocky does not want anything to do with him trying to leave that life behind but he ends up warming up to the kid and becomes his trainer. Adonis goes by his mother's last name trying not to follow in his father's shadow but towards the end of the movie, he realizes that owning up to your heritage is not a bad thing. This is a great movie it has the feel and charm of the first movie and Sylvester Stallone is excellent as always and he is the only original that returns we find out that Paulie died and that Robert his son moved away. The only new major characters we meet is Adonis, Bianca played by Tessa Thompson and Pretty Ricky Conlan played by Tony Bellew who is Adonis's opponent. The acting is great, the story is great, the directing is great and the music is great. We also find out that Rocky has cancer and watching him get treatment and train Adonis in the hospital was awesome especially the part where he says that the nurse could go a couple of rounds. If you have not seen this movie then I recommend you do. This movie is Cinematastic rating 5/5

For me, that's my perfect ending. Honestly got teared up just typing this out haha.

(Yes I know, Talia is pretty old now, but I think with CGI advancements and practical effects today in studios, they can make it look seemless.)

Comment: This is the rocky follow up we needed. Rocky has been through a lot over the course of the 6 films. If we count the films chronology of events, he has been blind in 1 eye since the 2nd film, had a brain tumour from the 5th film, and has been through a lot since he was a simple boxer in 1. Now you have CREED, a film about someone who is trying to forge their own identity as a boxer while living in the shadow of his father, his mentor and their combined past. It's fitting that rocky hand over his legacy to the son of his greatest rival and friend. It's the passing of the torch to the next generation.

Comment:
I'm a diehard fan of the Rocky series & have no idea what this movie will be about...
The only thing I don't quiet understand about the series is, why does Apollo Creed's son feel like he has something to fight for, yet Rocky Balboa's son does not? 
Of course they're 2 different people, but they're the sons of the 2 greatest fictional boxers of all time, so surely it has to be in the genes right?
I mean it's like both son's were born into wealthiness, with the Creed family being much better off financially than the Balboa family, until Rocky took the torch away from Apollo that is, won it all, lost it all again, then got some of it back with the flourishing restaurant business.
Robert never had the heart of a fighter, yet Adonis has, so it's as if Apollo Creed's son (whom I'm guessing never knew his father) can relate to Rocky (as a father figure) much more than Rocky's own son can relate to his own father.
I know I'm just making assumptions... Guess I just have to watch the movie to know what it's all about.

Title: Creed - Official Trailer [HD]
Comment: Wow... this is like a "Boxing Cinematic Universe". This got me thinking... They could make boxing movie "crossovers"... In boxing movies, you always follow *one* protagonist. You see him go through his life's struggles, overcome obstacles, challenge himself and eventually win the big fight. In the meantime, his opponent is *always* portrayed as a "mean" tough guy with no relevant backstory. But what if the opponent *had* a backstory? Equally moving as the protagonist's? What if you make *TWO* separate boxing movies. Each about a different boxer's journey and prize fights... and in each of the fighters' solo movies, you would sometimes see small hints or cameos of the *other* fighter. Then, you would have them *both* meet in the ring in a *3rd* movie.  I personally think that would be awesome. It would give the final fight tremendous importance... (kind of like what Marvel does with its superheroes but in a *realistic* boxing world).

Title: Creed - Official Trailer [HD]
Comment:
Wow, that took me off guard! I thought 'Creed' was going to be a prequel, about Apollo Creed's rise to fame before the events of 'Rocky', which is why I was surprised at how modern the setting looked. Not even the line "your daddy died in the ring" tipped me off since I thought it was a foreboding call-forward to Apollo's eventual fate, showing that he accepted it when he began. I wasn't expecting it to be a SEQUEL, and I CERTAINLY wasn't expecting Sylvester Stallone to show up to be junior's mentor. This feels like it really could be as awesome as 'Rocky Balboa' after all, rather than the shameless cash-in I was concerned it might be when I first heard about it.

Hey, I wonder if young Creed will ever get to fight Mason 'The Line' Dixon? That'd be neat.

Comment: In Britain, slavery continued to be practiced following the fall of Rome and sections of Hywel the Good's laws dealt with slaves in medieval Wales. The trade particularly picked up after the Viking invasions, with major markets at Chester and Bristol supplied by Danish, Mercian, and Welsh raiding of one another's borderlands. At the time of the Domesday Book, nearly 10% of the English population were slaves. Slavery in early medieval Europe was so common that the Roman Catholic Church repeatedly prohibited it — or at least the export of Christian slaves to non-Christian lands was prohibited at e.g. the Council of Koblenz (922), the Council of London (1102), and the Council of Armagh (1171). In 1452, Pope Nicholas V issued the papal bull Dum Diversas, granting the kings of Spain and Portugal the right to reduce any "Saracens (antiquated term referring to Muslims), pagans and any other unbelievers" to perpetual slavery, legitimizing the slave trade as a result of war. The approval of slavery under these conditions was reaffirmed and extended in his Romanus Pontifex bull of 1455. However, Pope Paul III forbade enslavement of the native Americans in 1537 in his papal bull Sublimus Dei. Dominican friars who arrived at the Spanish settlement at Santo Domingo strongly denounced the enslavement of the local native Americans. Along with other priests, they opposed their treatment as unjust and illegal in an audience with the Spanish king and in the subsequent royal commission.

Title: Creed - Official Trailer [HD]
Comment:
Ah, now picture this. Creed is a great fighter, trained by the best ever, Rocky Balboa, but he's a rich boy, he doesn't have the eye of a killer from the streets. Rocky had that naturally in the ring, but he doesn't know how to teach someone else to have the eye of a killer, he's too nice! He gets far but not yet to the top. He's still in his dads shadow. To get the eye of a snarling mad wrecking machine that just won't quit Rocky sets up a secret match behind closed doors. Creed enters the ring in a run down gym, there is no-one there. A door out of shot slams shut, Creed looks over, his face changes from anticipation to confused awe. We hear a man step into the ring, the camera pans over to where Creed is looking and reveals it to be Ivan Drago. Though much to Creeds disapproval, Rocky's plan to turn Creed from nothing more than a man living in his dad's shadow and wanting to prove that he is his dads equal into snarling mad wrecking machine that just won't quit works instantly. Now there is no stopping Creed from getting to the top and along the way, he learns to forgive Ivan which allows him to finally bury his demons. 

Yeah it's corny but it just feels so Rocky like :)

Title: Creed - Official Trailer [HD]
Comment:
"I want to see the story behind Apollo's son. Apollo's story is over. He was a good character; inspirational, powerful, prolific. Rocky's story is over. He's old, he's retired, he's done. Now I want to see what happens when that legend continues to thrive. I want to see what happens when legends are killed, I want to see what happens when legends are reborn. I want to see the new story behind Apollo's son."

Wow, whoever pitched this idea to Hollywood, I thank you so much. It's been a long time since we've got something with this much cinematic promise. Seriously, give that guy a raise or something. He's breathing new life into a stale industry.
